To implement the longest common subsequence problem in Java, we can use the following approach:

1. Define the two input strings as two arrays of characters.
2. Initialize two pointers, one for each string, at the first character of each string.
3. Compare the characters of the two pointers. If the characters match, increment a counter. If the characters do not match, choose the smaller pointer and move it forward.
4. Repeat steps 3 and 4 until the end of one or both strings is reached.
5. Return the value of the counter as the LCS.

Here is the code in Java:
```java
public class LCS {
    public static int lcs(String s1, String s2) {
        int m = s1.length();
        int n = s2.length();
        int[] dp = new int[m + 1];
        for (int i = 1; i <= m; i++) {
            dp[i] = new int[n + 1];
            for (int j = 1; j <= n; j++) {
                dp[i][j] = 0;
            }
        }
        for (int i = 1; i <= m; i++) {
            for (int j = 1; j <= n; j++) {
                if (s1.charAt(i - 1) == s2.charAt(j - 1)) {
                    dp[i][j] = dp[i - 1][j - 1] + 1;
                } else {
                    dp[i][j] = Math.max(dp[i - 1][j], dp[i][j - 1]);
                }
            }
        }
        return dp[m][n];
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String s1 = "ABCDGH";
        String s2 = "AEDFHR";
        int lcs = lcs(s1, s2);
        System.out.println("LCS: " + lcs);
    }
}
```
In the above code, we first initialize two arrays, `dp`, of size `m + 1` and `n + 1`, where `m` and `n` are the lengths of the input strings. We then initialize the first element of each array to 0.

We then loop over the characters of the first string, `s1`, and for each character, we loop over the characters of the second string, `s2`. If the characters match, we increment the value of the corresponding element in the `dp` array. If the characters do not match, we choose the smaller pointer and move it forward.

