 A stack is a Last-In-First-Out (LIFO) data structure that allows elements to be added and removed from the top of the stack. The basic operations of a stack include pushing elements onto the stack and popping elements off the stack.

A queue is a First-In-First-Out (FIFO) data structure that allows elements to be added and removed from the rear of the queue. The basic operations of a queue include enqueuing elements onto the queue and dequeuing elements off the queue.

Here is an example of pseudocode for a stack:
```sql
class Stack {
  element top; // top element of stack
  element bottom; // bottom element of stack
  int size; // number of elements in stack

  void push(element e) {
    // add element to stack
    size++;
    bottom = e;
  }

  element pop() {
    // remove and return top element of stack
    element ret = top;
    top = bottom;
    bottom = null;
    size--;
    return ret;
  }
}
```
