Encapsulation is the process of hiding the internal workings of an object from the outside world. This is achieved by using access modifiers such as public, private, and protected.

Inheritance is the process of creating a new class based on an existing class. The new class inherits all the properties and methods of the existing class and can also add or modify them.

Polymorphism is the ability of an object to take on many forms. In OOP, this is achieved through method overloading and method overriding.

Abstraction is the process of simplifying complex systems by focusing on the essential features and ignoring the non-essential ones.

Procedural programming, on the other hand, is a programming paradigm that is based on the concept of procedures or functions. In procedural programming, procedures are used to perform tasks, and data is passed as input to the procedures. The main features and characteristics of procedural programming include sequential execution, simple data structures, and a focus on algorithms.

In procedural programming, the code is organized into procedures that are executed sequentially. The data is passed as input to the procedures, and the output is returned as a result.

Procedural programming uses simple data structures such as arrays and records. The data structures are used to store and manipulate data.

Procedural programming is focused on algorithms, which are step-by-step procedures for solving a problem.

